	  <texsupport href="../Analysis_TeXSupport.xml"/>
	
	  <title>Comparison Test for Series: Examples</title>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Show that the series</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \dfrac{1}{(3+(-1)^n)^n}</latex>
			      </math.display>
			      <para>
            <para.body>converges to a number.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The <math>
                        <latex>n</latex>
                     </math>-th summand of the given series is</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>a_n\ :=\ \dfrac{1}{(3+(-1)^n)^n}\ \leq\ \dfrac{1}{2^n}\ =:\ b_n</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>for all <math>
                        <latex>n\geq 0</latex>
                     </math>. The sequence <math>
                        <latex>(b_n)</latex>
                     </math> provides the summands for the geometric series</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \dfrac{1}{2^n}\ =\ \dfrac{1}{1 - (1/2)}\ =\ 2</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Therefore the criteria for convergence of a series to a number by comparison are satisfied, and we conclude that <math>
                        <latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_n</latex>
                     </math> converges to a number <math>
                        <latex>\leq 2</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
	
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Show that the series</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \dfrac{n^2}{3^n}</latex>
			      </math.display>
			      <para>
            <para.body>converges to a number.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>This series is already a bit more challenging to analyze. However, with the tools of differential calculus, we will be able to show that</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>a_n\ :=\ \dfrac{n^2}{3^n}\ \leq\ \left( \dfrac{2}{3}\right)^n\ =:\ b_n</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>for <math>
                        <latex>n</latex>
                     </math> sufficiently large. The series <math>
                        <latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}b_n</latex>
                     </math> is a geometric series which converges to <math>
                        <latex>3</latex>
                     </math>. So <math>
                        <latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_n</latex>
                     </math> converges to a number.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
	
	
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Show that </para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \dfrac{1}{n + (1+(-1)^n)}\ =\ +\infty</latex>
			      </math.display>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>(b_n)</latex>
                     </math> is the sequence of summands of the given series, then</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
b_n\ =\ \left\{
\begin{array}{rcl}
\dfrac{1}{n+2} &amp; \text{if} &amp; \text{$n$ even} \\
\dfrac{1}{n} &amp; \text{if} &amp; \text{$n$ odd}
\end{array}\right.
					
				</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Thus, for <math>
                        <latex>n\geq 2</latex>
                     </math>,</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>a_n\ :=\ \dfrac{1}{2n}\ \leq\ \dfrac{1}{n+2}\ \leq\ \dfrac{1}{n+ (1+(-1)^n)}\ =\ b_n</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The series <math>
                        <latex>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} a_n</latex>
                     </math> is related to the harmonic series:</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \dfrac{1}{2n}\ =\ \dfrac{1}{2}\cdot \left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \dfrac{1}{n}\right)\ =\ \dfrac{1}{2}\cdot (+\infty)\ =\ +\infty</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Therefore <math>
                        <latex>\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}b_n = +\infty</latex>
                     </math> by comparison.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
	
</showme.pack>
